[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating testing dependencies**\n\nI’m thinking about using normal tests with javax.inject annotations, but I wonder if I need optional JUnit or TestNG since the library imports these. I might not always want to use InjectedTest classes; it seems like meaningful coverage could be reached without them by using alternatives like SisuGuice. I should decide if extra dependencies are necessary beyond the scaffold. The generated tests include the target library and its transitive dependencies, so I'll need to figure this out carefully.\n\n**Assessing dependency needs**\n\nI'm considering whether to add extra Maven dependencies, like a database driver, though there are no external services in this case. Optional JUnit or TestNG integrations may be needed for testing injected classes, but the existing build lacks JUnit 4. I’m curious if these classes require transitive dependencies. After looking at existing tests, they don't import JUnit, but generated tests might. I think I should only advise optional dependencies if they're genuinely necessary for meaningful coverage.\n\n**Evaluating test setup guidance**\n\nI’m considering the idea of including environment or system property test setup guidance, especially since the instructions suggest not to repeat deterministic entries. If there aren’t any deterministic entries, I'm curious about the necessary compile guidance. The allowed setup includes environment properties and test code setup, but it asks for no action unless extra setup is critical. I might need to resolve dependencies through Gradle to clarify the compile classpath, particularly since SisuGuice is included as a transitive dependency. Should I also use Maven?", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_05ed24599ec52d50016a3fd9f391e88190baef03bb2fdd25a4\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqP9n-3UJmF6f5syUs43VWJzZBse6UoYVADhrwI